{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/387"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.23,0.17,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52488"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3459"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52488"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of severe upper abdominal pain following an alcoholic binge. He feels nauseous and has vomited twice. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is tender in the epigastrium. An ultrasound performed on admission shows pancreatic swelling without evidence of gallstones. He is admitted to hospital and treated supportively with analgesia and gut rest. His pain settles over the next week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt a 6-week follow-up appointment, the patient is well and pain-free with a non-tender abdomen, but his serum amylase remains persistently elevated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pseudocyst of the pancreas","Low grade pancreatic necrosis","Chronic pancreatitis","Pancreatic abscess","Pancreatic duct obstruction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has experienced an episode of acute pancreatitis, likely alcohol-induced. Given that he has recovered with no residual pain or other complaints, but his serum amylase remains persistently elevated at 6 weeks, the most likely diagnosis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudocyst of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E as a complication of his acute pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPancreatic pseudocysts typically develop 4-6 weeks after an episode of acute pancreatitis and are characterized by a collection of pancreatic juice enclosed by a wall of fibrous or granulation tissue. They are associated with persistently elevated pancreatic enzyme levels, such as amylase, which is seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow grade pancreatic necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication of pancreatitis that usually occurs within the first four weeks of the disease process. It would likely be associated with ongoing symptoms and would not explain the isolated finding of elevated amylase at 6 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-term condition characterized by persistent inflammation of the pancreas leading to deranged pancreatic function and structural changes. It typically develops over years following recurrent episodes of acute pancreatitis. Amylase levels are not necessarily elevated due to loss of pancreatic function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with more severe illness such as sepsis, ongoing pain, and fever. The patient\u0027s well appearance and lack of symptoms at 6 weeks make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic duct obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would typically result in signs such as jaundice and pain, and potentially signs of infection if the obstruction becomes infected. The absence of these symptoms makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the timing of 6 weeks post-acute pancreatitis, the patient\u0027s well appearance, and the isolated finding of persistently elevated serum amylase are most consistent with a pancreatic pseudocyst.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudocysts of the pancreas are a complication of acute pancreatitis that can result in persistently raised pancreatic enzyme levels."],"references":["Sarr MG, Banks PA, Bollen TL, Dervenis C, Gooszen HG, et al. The new revised classification of acute pancreatitis. Surg Clin North Am. 2013;93(3):549-62. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23632143/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-06T11:17:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T11:19:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52488"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","lin